The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Exide buys out arm
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Exide buys out arm
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                          STAKE HIKE                                  
	Calcutta, July 13: Exide Industries  the countrys largest lead acid storage battery maker  has acquired the residual stake in its subsidiary Leadage Alloys India Ltd.        
	At present, the Rajan Raheja company holds a 51 per cent stake in the lead smelting unit.         
	With this acquisition, Exide now has two wholly owned smelting units for captive consumption to meet its requirement of lead and lead alloys, the key raw materials in storage batteries.        
	Leadage has its facility in Kolar district of Karnataka. It has achieved a turnover of Rs 546 crore and profit before tax of Rs 54 crore for the year ended March 31, representing a growth of 23 per cent and 621 per cent, respectively, over the previous fiscal.        
	Exide had acquired the initial stake in 2008 to keep a tab on volatile raw material prices  a move that had benefited the company substantially.        
	Profit growth        
	Exide today reported a 35 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 165.34 crore during the first quarter of 2010-11 against Rs 122.40 crore a year ago. Net sales grew 27 per cent to Rs 1,151.68 crore from Rs 903.11 crore a year ago.                                                                                                                                      
